      "for anyDayReplacement = false, filterEndOfMonth = false, onlyLatest = true, " +
      "for the case that even with anyDayReplacement = false the selection priority algorithm breaks ties" in {
        super[ScalaCheckDrivenPropertyChecks].forAll(genScenariosWithReadingInputs(forEndOfMonth = false)) {
          scenariosWithReadingInputs =>
            logger.debug("scenariosWithReadingInputs: " + scenariosWithReadingInputs)
            // We want to create a situation where we know from the scenario generation a scenario which has the latest
            // day (as all scenarios use different days). Within this scenario we know that the expected readings
            // will get priority over the other readings when requesting them via method findReadingsByProperty().
            // We need a setup that we know the latest expected reading, and that all other readings have no later
            // date/time than this latest expected reading. At the same time, we want that for that latest date/time
            // there are many readings, so that we can test the the prio algorithm breaks ties. Thus we must make sure
            // that there are other readings for this same latest date/time.
            // The implementation of this setup is: per scenario find from the expected readings the one with the latest
            // consumptionDate (date/time), then copy over that consumption date to all the other readings of this
            // scenario. This modifies all scenarios, while it would only be needed for the scenario on the latest day,
            // but it is easier to implement and does not harm.
            // These new other readings per scenario would not be expected to be returned, as they have a lower prio.
            // However, the prio is a convoluted result of reading type, transport type and medium type. And the
            // readings database table has a primary key including reading type (and date/time and meterport), but not
            // including transport type nor medium type. Thus, when the readings are inserted to the database table,
            // care must be taken that no expected readings are overwritten by "other" readings.
            // One idea would be to insert the "other" readings before inserting the expected readings, as otherwise the
            // "other" readings may overwrite the expected readings. With the full cross-product of all possible "other"
            // readings there would be many "other" readings which would overwrite other "other" readings.
            // But using createFilledMdrUnderTestFromScenarios(), which under the hood uses
            // MeterDataRepositoryImpl.insertReadings(), with a sequence of first "other" and then "expected" readings
            // does not work, as it will not in all cases guarantee that the readings later in the sequence will
            // overwrite a reading earlier in the sequence. There is especially a special domain rule to not overwrite
            // a PDA value with a non-PDA value. This breaks the idea to let the readings overwrite each other during
            // insert.
            // Thus we need to upfront make sure to order and select the "other" readings such that the insertReadings()
            // would not kick in by filtering out readings, nor the readings database table to kick in by overwriting
            // readings. We simulate the database table primary key via a groupBy and we simulate to insert first the
            // other readings and then the expected readings by adding to the grouped-by Map of "other" readings the
            // grouped-by Map of expected readings, so that the expected readings overwrite the "other" readings in the
            // Map. This way we create a sequence of readings where we selected a subset of "other" readings such that
            // they neither overwrite expected readings nor other "other" readings.
            // The test then checks that the single returned value is from the scenario with the latest consumptionDate
            // and that despite the fact that there are other readings with that same date/time still the expected
            // reading is returned. This proves that the prio is used for onlyLatest even without anyDayReplacement.
            val expectedReadings = scenariosWithReadingInputs
              .flatMap { case (_, expectedReadings, _) => expectedReadings }
            val expectedReadingInputs = expectedReadings
              .groupBy(readingInput => (readingInput.consumptionDate, readingInput.readingType))
              .map { case (key, readings) => (key, readings.head) } // as there is only one reading per key anyway
            val otherReadingInputs = scenariosWithReadingInputs
              .flatMap { case (_, expectedReadings, otherReadings) =>
                val latestConsumptionDate = expectedReadings.map(_.consumptionDate).max
                otherReadings.map(_.copy(consumptionDate = latestConsumptionDate))
              }
              .groupBy(readingInput => (readingInput.consumptionDate, readingInput.readingType))
              .map { case (key, readings) => (key, Random.shuffle(readings).head) } // take one randomly, as the others would be overwritten in the database anyway
            val uniqueReadingInputs = otherReadingInputs.concat(expectedReadingInputs).values // let expected readings overwrite other readings
            val mdrUnderTest = createFilledMdrUnderTestFromScenarios(uniqueReadingInputs)
            val readingsReceived = mdrUnderTest.findReadingsByProperty(
              propertyId = meterPortConfig.propertyId,
              filterDevices = Set.empty,
              filterExecPlan = None, // typically not asked for
              filterFrom,
              filterTo,
              filterReadingTypes = Set.empty, // filtering out of scope for this test
              filterServiceTypes = Set.empty, // typically not asked for
              filterTransportTypes = Set.empty, // filtering out of scope for this test
              filterEndOfMonth = false,
              anyDayReplacement = false,
              onlyLatest = true,
              filterInstalled = false
            )
            // The test setup creates 2 expected readings with regards to the ANY prio algorithm.
            // Due to the primary key of the readings database table and with the current creation of random test data
            // (see above) both readings are guaranteed to be inserted to the readings database table.
            // With onlyLatest = true will return the latest reading. Therefore, there is exactly one of the 2 expected
            // readings with highest date/time, which is the one expected to be returned.
            val expectedReading = expectedReadings.maxBy(_.consumptionDate)
            readingsReceived.size shouldBe 1
            assert(compare(expectedReading, readingsReceived.head))
        }
      }

      "for anyDayReplacement = true, filterEndOfMonth = both, onlyLatest = true" in {
        super[ScalaCheckDrivenPropertyChecks].forAll(genScenariosWithReadingInputs) {
          case (scenariosWithReadingInputs, filterEndOfMonth) =>
